  "prompt": "When people say \"Maths\" instead of \"Math\" are they indicating plurality in some way?",
  "response": "The difference between \"maths\" and \"math\" primarily comes down to regional variations in English rather than indicating plurality. In the United States and Canada, the abbreviation \"math\" is commonly used, while in the United Kingdom, Ireland, Australia, and several other English-speaking countries, \"maths\" is the standard abbreviation. Both terms refer to the same concept and are short for \"mathematics,\" which is inherently plural in form but singular in meaning, referring to the field of study as a whole. The choice of \"math\" or \"maths\" does not imply a difference in meaning or plurality, but rather reflects regional preferences in language.",
